# Flutter Conventions

## Context
- Apply when creating or modifying any Flutter widget, provider, or screen.
- The app is a **single-flow kiosk** — not a general navigation app. Architecture reflects this.

## Requirements

### Feature Structure
- `lib/features/<name>/` — each feature owns:
  - `models/` — `@freezed` data classes
  - `providers/` — `@riverpod` annotated notifiers and async providers
  - `screens/` — `StatelessWidget` or `ConsumerWidget` screens; thin, no business logic
- `lib/core/` — shared: `config/`, `logging/`, `errors/`, `database/`, `payment/`
- `lib/app/` — `app.dart` (MaterialApp), `router.dart` (GoRouter), `theme.dart`

### State Management
- Riverpod 2.x with `@riverpod` code generation — no manual `Provider(...)` construction.
- Providers in `<feature>/providers/` files, `part` of their `.g.dart` counterpart.
- `AsyncNotifier` for async state with loading/error/data. `Notifier` for pure sync state.
- State objects are `@freezed` — no mutable fields on state classes.
- **No `setState` for business logic** — `setState` is only for local widget animation/visual state.
- **No BuildContext across async gaps** — check `mounted` or use `ref.context` pattern.

### Navigation
- GoRouter only. Routes defined in `lib/app/router.dart`. Named via `KioskRoutes` constants.
- **No `Navigator.push` or `Navigator.pop`** anywhere in feature code.
- Kiosk flow: `Attract → TicketSelection → Payment/:orderId → Confirmation/:orderId → Attract`.
- `Payment` and `Confirmation` have `PopScope(canPop: false)` — no back navigation.
- Returning to Attract after confirmation uses `context.go(KioskRoutes.attract)` — full stack reset.

### Widgets
- Prefer `ConsumerWidget` over `StatefulWidget` when state is in Riverpod.
- Keep `build()` methods under ~60 lines — extract sub-widgets when larger.
- Large touch targets: minimum `Size(120, 64)` for interactive elements. Kiosk target: `Size(180, 72)`.
- `const` constructors wherever possible — `prefer_const_constructors` is enforced.
- No hardcoded colours or font sizes in widgets — use `Theme.of(context)` only.

### Kiosk UX Rules
- Every screen that is not `Attract` must implement idle timeout (reset to `Attract` after `AppConfig.idleTimeoutSeconds`).
- `Payment` screen starts the SumUp charge immediately on `initState` post-frame callback — no extra tap needed.
- `Confirmation` screen auto-returns to `Attract` after 15 seconds via `Timer`.
- No keyboard shown to public users — all input is tap/button only. Admin PIN uses numeric keyboard only.

## Examples

<example>
// Good: ConsumerWidget, GoRouter navigation, no business logic in build
class ConfirmationScreen extends ConsumerWidget {
  const ConfirmationScreen({super.key, required this.orderId});
  final String orderId;

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context, WidgetRef ref) {
    return Scaffold(
      body: Center(
        child: FilledButton(
          onPressed: () => context.go(KioskRoutes.attract),
          child: const Text('Done'),
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}
</example>

<example type="invalid">
// Bad: Navigator.push, setState for business logic, hardcoded size
Navigator.push(context, MaterialPageRoute(builder: (_) => PaymentScreen()));
setState(() { _isPaying = true; }); // business logic in widget
SizedBox(height: 48, width: 200) // hardcoded, not from theme
</example>

## Critical Rules
- NEVER use `Navigator.push` or `Navigator.pop` — use GoRouter.
- NEVER put business logic in `build()` or `setState`.
- NEVER hardcode colours, sizes, or fonts — use `Theme.of(context)`.
- ALWAYS use `PopScope(canPop: false)` in Payment and Confirmation screens.
- ALWAYS implement idle timeout on every screen except Attract.
- ALWAYS use `const` constructors where possible.
